{{Infobox language |name=Algerian Sign Language |states=[[Algeria]], [[Oujda]] |speakers=?<!--The estimate of 220,000 from Ethnologue's reference, IMB, is the number of deaf people.--> |familycolor=sign |fam1=[[French Sign Language family|French Sign]] |iso3=asp |glotto=alge1235 |glottorefname=Algerian Sign Language }}
'''Algerian Sign Language''' (French: ''Langue des signes algérienne (LSA)'', Tamazight: ''Tutlayt Tagugamt n Lezzayer'', Arabic: لغة الإشارة الجزائرية ) is the [[sign language]] most commonly used in [[Algeria]]. It was officially recognized by the Algerian law on the protection and promotion of persons with a disability enacted on May 8, 2002.
It has influenced the deaf community in [[Oujda]] in northern [[Morocco]].<ref>{{ethnolink|asp|Algerian Sign Language}} at ''Ethnologue''</ref>
