{{Infobox writer |name = Francisco de Paula Ney |image = Francisco de Paula Ney.jpg |imagesize = 200px |caption = A photograph depicting Ney |birth_date = {{birth date|1858|2|2|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Aracati]], [[Ceará]], [[Brazil]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1897|11|13|1858|2|2|df=y}} |death_place = [[Rio de Janeiro|Rio de Janeiro City]], [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]] |occupation = [[Poet]], journalist |nationality = Brazilian |movement = [[Parnassianism]] }} '''Francisco de Paula Ney''' (February 2, 1858 &ndash; November 13, 1897) was a [[Brazil]]ian poet and journalist. A pre-eminent figure of the [[Bohemianism|bohemian]] [[Rio de Janeiro]] of the ''[[Belle Époque]]'', he was a friend of [[Coelho Neto]], [[Aluísio Azevedo]] and [[Olavo Bilac]]. He was a poet famous for writing anonymous [[satire]]s and [[joke]]s for the journals where he worked.
==External links== *[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706152233/http://www.enciclopedianordeste.com.br/010.php A biography and some poems by Francisco de Paula Ney] {{pt icon}}
